WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
[Field recording: morning market sounds]

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Narrator: Sound is memory before it becomes language.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:20.000
For many in the African diaspora, the sounds of home carry a kind of grief that photographs cannot.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:30.000
Kwame: The first thing I looked for when I moved to London was somewhere that sounded right.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:45.000
Not looked right — sounded right. I found a market near Peckham. Fridays only.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:55.000
Amara: You carry the hills with you.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:10.000
That's what my grandmother told me. She meant the sound of wind across the hills.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:15.000
Tolu: I never left, so for me it's the opposite.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:30.000
I watch my cousins come back and I see them hear Lagos for the first time again.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:45.000
Narrator: What unites all three voices is not nostalgia — it's attention.

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:10.000
[Closing field recording: evening prayer call fading into city ambience]